+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EL3qTUn56RDpo4r8jVNZpq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Interesting — the \"rejects connection for non-existent document\" and \"rejects connection with invalid path\" tests PASS (they don't use `connectWs`), but all tests that use `connectWs` fail. The issue is in the `connectWs` function. The WS `open` event listener might be registered after the event has already fired.\n\nLet me check: `new WS(url)` → the WS connects to the server immediately. If the connection is established before we call `ws.on('open', ...)`, we'd miss the event. But that shouldn't happen since it's all in the same sync block. Unless vitest is doing something weird.\n\nWait — let me look at the failing vs passing tests more carefully. The passing tests create `new WS(url)` and immediately call `waitForMessage`. The `message` event comes after `open`, so they catch it. But `connectWs` waits for `open` — which if already emitted, would hang.\n\nActually, Node.js event emitters don't work that way — `ws.on('open', ...)` is registered before the event loop progresses. The constructor starts the connection but the actual TCP connection happens asynchronously. So we should be fine.\n\nBut wait — maybe the issue is with how vitest handles the `ws` import. Let me check if `WS` constructor from vitest's import is actually the right thing:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2428,"cache_read_input_tokens":55252,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2428},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4d593c82-8c63-4015-83a0-12028d6e913b","uuid":"19115e83-7a90-4959-8afe-60494a5b99f3"}
